<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-934-722  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 934 722.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Dec 4 1989 v35 n1787 p32(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM, DEC, HP focus on plant automation. (product development plansfor computer-aided manufacturing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dunn, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer-aided manufacturing plans for IBM, DEC and HP focus onflexible networking schemes, simplified programming capabilitiesand strong support for third-party software.andP;  IBM is moving awayfrom C language programming to user-friendly, icon-driven fourthgeneration languages.andP;  DEC's Network Applications Supportenvironment allows MSDOS, OS/2, Macintosh operating system, Unixand VMS to interoperate in a single network.andP;  HP is developing areal-time database, an interactive visual interface and a deviceinterface, all of which can be accessed through high-levelcommands.andP;  All three firms tried to allay fears that thesophisticated user interfaces would degrade system performance.andO;Representatives for the three firms spoke at a conferencesponsored by Advanced Manufacturing Research Inc.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development)Digital Equipment Corp. (product development)Hewlett-Packard Co. (product development)Advanced Manufacturing Research Inc. (conferences and meetings).andO;Ticker:    HWP; DEC; IBM.andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentComputer-aided manufacturingConferencesUser-FriendlinessComputer-Integrated ManufacturingFlexible Manufacturing Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>